<br>
But alas, one by one we were outnumbered and dropped, a call came out, HEALERS AND SHAMAN FLEE. So we did, hoping Eir would bless me enough to raise my fallen comrades. And thats when we saw him, a lone albion caster medding on a hill. With a war cry to Eir, I rushed the fool, and rooted his feet to the ground. The shaman joined me, wishing this one dead for our fallen comrades. A few swings and a stun later, the albion said something I couldnt understand, probably a cry to his god for mercy, and gave his last breath. My hammer was bloodied, sweat rolled down my back, and then, I knew what it was to be a Shank.<br>
<br>
<img src =http://www.strike9.com/eq/file.aspx/path=/Erya/fullsize/sshot017.jpg><br>
<br>
/ooc Notice my last words on the chat, I told several of the other group that was with us, "its time to run!" They decided to completely ignore me, and rush the force of 40 albions. The end was quite what I expected..... dead midgardians (sigh)<br>
<br>
These two were from days before when we fought against a large force of Hibbies, the deaths brought a smile to my face.<br>
<br>
<img src =http://www.strike9.com/eq/file.aspx/path=/Erya/fullsize/sshot015.jpg><br>
<br>
<br>
And this one soon after when we sprang on his friends and him from ambush right outside their keep.<br>
<br>
<img src =http://www.strike9.com/eq/file.aspx/path=/Erya/fullsize/sshot014.jpg><br>
<br>
Friends, and blooded shanks, I have followed ye from all over, and I stand before you with tha blood of my enemies on me hands. The sweet sound of victory quickly quiets out tha scream of death, and I like tha former better.<br>
<br>
*Erya bows low and steps back looking into the eyes of Woden and others*<br>
<br>
<br>
I await your word.<br>
